{\plain \fs24 \b INFERNO CANTO 03}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 1-9.}{\plain \fs24   Modern editions vary in using capital or lower-case letters for this inscription over \softline
the gate of hell.  Lacking Dante's autograph MS, we can only conjecture.  For the view that the \softline
model for these words is found in the victorious inscriptions found on Roman triumphal arches, \softline
sculpted in capital letters in stone, see Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i Allegory in Dante{\u8219\'27}s "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24  [Princeton, \softline
Princeton University Press, 1969]), p. 300.  In this view every condemned sinner is being led \softline
back captive to 'that Rome of which Christ is Roman' (}{\plain \fs24 \i Purg}{\plain \fs24 . XXXII.102), 'under the yoke' into \softline
God's holy kingdom, where he or she will be eternally a prisoner.  \par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 1-3.}{\plain \fs24   For the city as the poem's centering image of political life, the hellish earthly city, \softline
resembling Florence, 'which stands for the self and against the common good,' and the heavenly \softline
city, an idealized view of imperial Rome, see Joan Ferrante (}{\plain \fs24 \i The Political Vision of the "Divine \softline
Comedy"}{\plain \fs24  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1984]), pp. 41-42.  The anaphora, or repetition, \softline
of the phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i per me si va}{\plain \fs24 , as it comes 'uttered' by the gate of hell itself in the first three verses, \softline
has a ring of inevitable doom about it.  A student (Charlene Cosman, Princeton '76) once \softline
suggested that it also contains a self-conscious gesture on the part of its author: it is }{\plain \fs24 \i through him}{\plain \fs24  \softline
that we visit this place of woe, suffering, and perdition.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 4.}{\plain \fs24   'Justice moved my maker on high.'  Dante's verse may seem to violate the \softline
Aristotelian/Thomist definition of God as the 'unmoved mover.'  Strictly speaking, }{\plain \fs24 \i nothing}{\plain \fs24  can \softline
'move' God, who Himself moves all things (even if He can be described in the Bible as feeling \softline
anger at humankind, etc.).  Dante's apparently 'theologically incorrect' statement shows the \softline
importance of his sense of justice as the central force in the universe, so encompassing that it \softline
may be seen as, in a sense, God's 'muse,' as well as the primary subject of the poem.  The word \softline
in its noun form appears fully thirty-five times in the poem (once in Latin at }{\plain \fs24 \i Par}{\plain \fs24 . XVIII.91).  See \softline
Allan H. Gilbert (}{\plain \fs24 \i Dante's Conception of Justice}{\plain \fs24  [Durham, NC: Duke University Press, 1925] -- \softline
but see also Dino Bigongiari's sharply critical review [}{\plain \fs24 \i Essays on Dante and Medieval Culture}{\plain \fs24 , \softline
ed. Henry Paolucci (New York: The Bagehot Council, 2000 [1964]), pp. 86-91] and Hollander, \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Dante and Paul's "five words with understanding}{\plain \fs24 ," Occasional Papers, No. 1, Center for \softline
Medieval and Early Renaissance Texts and Studies [Binghamton, NY: Medieval and \softline
Renaissance Texts and Studies, 1992], pp. 40-41).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 5-6.}{\plain \fs24   The three attributes of the Christian God, Power, Wisdom, and Love, are nearly \softline
universally recognized as informing these two verses.  Hell is of God's making, not an \softline
independent 'city' of rebels, but a totally dependent }{\plain \fs24 \i polis}{\plain \fs24  of those who had rebelled against their \softline
maker.  For the post-biblical concept of the Trinity, especially as it was advanced in St. \softline
Augustine's }{\plain \fs24 \i De Trinitate}{\plain \fs24 , where Father, Son, and Holy Spirit is each identified by one of these \softline
attributes, respectively, see G. Fallani, "Trinit{\f2 \'42}" (ED.1976.5), pp. 718-21.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 7-8.}{\plain \fs24   The apparent difficulty of these verses (perhaps reflected in Dante's difficulty in \softline
understanding the writing over the gate,}{\plain \fs24 \i  Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.12) is resolved once we understand that here \softline
'eternal' is used to mean 'sempiternal,' that is, as having had a beginning in time but lasting ever \softline
after.  Only God, who is not created but all-creating, may be considered eternal.  See Mazzoni \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: \softline
Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 331-36.  Mazzoni, in agreement with Bruno Nardi (}{\plain \fs24 \i La caduta di Lucifero e 
l'autenticit{\f2 \'42} della "Quaestio de aqua et terra}{\plain \fs24 " [Torino, S.E.I. (Lectura Dantis Romana): 1959] -- \softline
now in Nardi, }{\plain \fs24 \i "Lecturae" e altri studi danteschi}{\plain \fs24 , ed. R. Abardo [Firenze: Le Lettere, 1990], p. \softline
17), allows this status to three classes of being: angels, prime matter (that is, the potential form \softline
of the as yet uncreated world), and the heavenly spheres.  For an apt description of Christ's \softline
Judgment of the damned, see Matthew 25:41, 25:46: 'Then shall he say also unto them on the left \softline
hand, Depart from me, ye cursed, into everlasting fire, prepared for the devil and his angels....  \softline
And these shall go away into everlasting punishment: but the righteous into life eternal.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 9.}{\plain \fs24   A curiosity about which there has been only a modicum of speculation results from \softline
the closeness of this verse to one in the opening verses of the first scene of the third act of \softline
Plautus's comedy }{\plain \fs24 \i Bacchides}{\plain \fs24 : 'Pandite atque aperite propere ianuam hanc Orci, opsecro: Nam \softline
equidem haud aliter esse duco: quippe quo nemo advenit Nisi quem }{\plain \fs24 \i spes reliquere omnes}{\plain \fs24 .'  For \softline
the first modern discussion see Edward Moore, }{\plain \fs24 \i Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 , First Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i Scripture and \softline
Classical Authors in Dante}{\plain \fs24  (Oxford: Clarendon, 1969 [1896]), p. 261n., and now R. Mercuri, \softline
"Plauto" (ED.1973.4), p. 555b.  For a much earlier citation, see Castelvetro (comm. to}{\plain \fs24 \i  Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.9-10).  There is general agreement that Dante could not have known the texts of Plautus directly \softline
(he does, however, name the Roman playwright at }{\plain \fs24 \i Purg}{\plain \fs24 . XXII.98), with the resultant \softline
understanding that Dante found the lines cited in one }{\plain \fs24 \i florilegium}{\plain \fs24  or another, even if no one has \softline
as yet produced such a manuscript in order to confirm this theory.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 10.}{\plain \fs24   Are the letters of these words 'dark in hue,' as are the inset carvings over actual gates, \softline
begrimed by time (or, as some early commentators urged, because they are hellishly menacing)?  \softline
Or are they rhetorically difficult, and 'dark' in that respect?  The phrase 'rhetorical colors' to \softline
indicate the rhetor's stylistic techniques is familiar from classical rhetoric and is found in Dante, \softline
e.g., in }{\plain \fs24 \i Vita nuova}{\plain \fs24  XXV.7 and XXV.10.  (For this usage in Dante see Domenico Consoli, \softline
"colore" [ED.1970.2], p. 65b.)  Most of the early commentators are drawn, however, to the first \softline
hypothesis (dark in color), while several recent ones prefer the latter.  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un \softline
nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), \softline
pp. 337-42, gives good reasons for favoring the ancient interpretation, opposing the reading \softline
offered by Pagliaro (}{\plain \fs24 \i Ulisse}{\plain \fs24 : }{\plain \fs24 \i ricerche semantiche sulla "Divina Commedia"}{\plain \fs24  [Messina-Florence: \softline
D'Anna, 1967]), pp. 762-65.  One should also consider the possibility that both meanings are \softline
present here.  In any case, whichever understanding one chooses, one will have to make a \softline
decision consonant with an interpretation of verse 12 (see the note to}{\plain \fs24 \i  Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.12).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 12.}{\plain \fs24   There is a fairly serious disagreement over the most probable interpretation of the \softline
words 'for me their meaning is hard.'  Our translation tries to reflect both possibilities, suggesting \softline
that one is clearly present, while the second may be only latent.  Are the words over the gate of \softline
hell (1) threatening to Dante?  Or (2) are they hard for him to understand?  It seems clear that the \softline
traveler is frightened by the dire advice tendered in verse 9, which would have him abandon all \softline
hope.  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  \softline
[Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 337-42, offers a lengthy gloss to this tercet (vv. 10-12 -- see the \softline
note to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.10).  It seems impossible not to accept his basic premise, namely that the context \softline
of the scene makes the meaning immediate and moral: the traveler is afraid, and Virgil reproves \softline
him for his fear (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.14-15).  This understanding is shared by the vast majority of the \softline
commentators, with a very few (the Ottimo, Boccaccio, Gregorio Di Siena) arguing for the \softline
understanding that the text insists only that Dante finds the meaning of the inscription difficult, 
and another handful arguing for a deliberately ambiguous meaning.  Critics like John Freccero, \softline
in his essay 'Infernal Irony: The Gates of Hell' (1983) in (}{\plain \fs24 \i Dante: The Poetics of Conversion}{\plain \fs24 , ed. \softline
Rachel Jacoff [Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1986], pp. 99-102), argue that the drama \softline
played out here is lodged in the difficulty of interpreting.  Without opposing that further \softline
interpretive dimension of the scene, one should probably insist on a literal understanding that \softline
squares with the text.  Freccero and others before him (e.g., Vandelli [comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.12]; \softline
Padoan [comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.12]) have heard the echo of John 6:60: 'Durus est hic sermo' (This is a \softline
hard saying).  But that context also, while allowing for the question of interpretive failure on the \softline
part of the disciples who do not understand what Jesus means when he says that those who eat of \softline
his flesh shall live forever, is rounded off by the }{\plain \fs24 \i moral}{\plain \fs24  failure of certain disciples (John 6:61; \softline
6:66).  For Dante, the seeming banishment of his hope is cause, not so much for distress at his \softline
intellectual failure so much as for fear of a punishment compelling enough to grasp -- an eternity \softline
in hell.  See Guiniforto delli Bargigi (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.10-12), paraphrasing the protagonist's \softline
remark as follows: 'non dico dura, perch'io non la intenda, ma dura {\f2 \'50}, perocch{\f2 \'50} dura cosa mi pare \softline
udir che io debba entrare in luogo di eterno dolore e lasciar la speranza di uscirne mai fuori, e \softline
per questo denota Dante, ch'ei temesse, e Virgilio lo confort{\f2 \'62} nella particella del testo che \softline
seguita.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 13-15.}{\plain \fs24   The comparison (}{\plain \fs24 \i come persona accorta}{\plain \fs24 ) lends Virgil authority in two regards: he \softline
is aware of Dante's moral shortcomings and he understands the underworld, since he has \softline
descended once before (see}{\plain \fs24 \i  Inf}{\plain \fs24 . IX.22-27; }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XXI.63).  The scene indeed has a classical \softline
precursor, as was noted, among the early commentators, by Boccaccio (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.13-15): \softline
the Sibyl's reassurance of threatened Aeneas (}{\plain \fs24 \i Aen}{\plain \fs24 . VI.261): 'Nunc animis opus, Aenea, nunc \softline
pectore firmo.'  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), p. 342, follows the tradition in the commentaries which \softline
argues that this tercet reaffirms the moral reading of }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.12, 'Maestro, il senso lor m'{\f2 \'50} duro.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 18.}{\plain \fs24   The 'good of the intellect' has long been understood as God.  See Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di \softline
un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), \softline
p. 343, citing }{\plain \fs24 \i Par}{\plain \fs24 . IV.116, where God is the 'fonte ond' ogne ver deriva' (the source from which \softline
all truth derives).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 21.}{\plain \fs24   The word }{\plain \fs24 \i segrete}{\plain \fs24  here does not mean 'secret' so much as 'cut off from' -- see Grabher \softline
(comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.21): '}{\plain \fs24 \i Segrete}{\plain \fs24  conserva la sua forza etimologica (da }{\plain \fs24 \i secerno}{\plain \fs24  [Latin 'separate \softline
from, cut off']) con immagine netta di separazione; qui: dal mondo e dalla conoscenza degli \softline
uomini' (cited by Mazzoni [}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  (Florence: Sansoni, 1967), p. 345]), i.e., those things that are hidden from the \softline
knowledge of mortals.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 22-30.}{\plain \fs24   This first sense impression of the underworld is exclusively aural.  We are \softline
probably meant to assume that Dante's eyes are not yet accustomed to the darkness of hell.  Cf. \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . IV.25-27 as well as }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XI.11, where his olfactory capacity must become used to the stench \softline
of nether hell.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
