{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 24.}{\plain \fs24   This first instance of Dante's weeping is part of a program of the protagonist's \softline
development in hell, in which he (very) gradually overcomes the twin temptations to weep for or 
feel fear at the situation of the sinners in Inferno.  See Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i Allegory in Dante{\u8219\'27}s \softline
"Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 ), pp. 301-7.  In the harsh moral code of the text, sympathy for the damned is \softline
always misplaced, if a certain admiration for some of their better qualities is allowed.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 25.}{\plain \fs24   The adjective }{\plain \fs24 \i diverse}{\plain \fs24  here means either 'different the one from the other' (on the \softline
model of the confused languages spoken after the construction of the Tower of Babel) or \softline
'strange,' a meaning for the adjective frequently found in Dante.  In our translation we have tried \softline
to allow for both meanings.  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": \softline
"Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), p. 348, gives further evidence for the first \softline
interpretation by citing}{\plain \fs24 \i  Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.123, where those who die in the wrath of God 'assemble here from \softline
every land,' a phrasing that calls attention to differing nationalities and thus suggests a plurality \softline
of tongues.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \tab 27.  E suon di man con elle}{\plain \fs24 .  Boccaccio's gloss (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . IX.49-51) to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . IX.50, \softline
'battiensi a palme,' which describes the Furies beating their breasts 'come qui [on earth] fanno le \softline
femine che gran dolor sentono, o mostran di sentire,' may help unravel this verse as well: the \softline
sound is that of hands striking the sinners' own bodies as they beat their breasts, as Boccaccio \softline
had already suggested in his gloss to this verse: 'come soglion far le femine battendosi a palme' \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.27-29).  See M. Barbi (}{\plain \fs24 \i Problemi di critica dantesca}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1934]), p. 267.  \softline
Others today (e.g., Bosco/Reggio [comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.27]) allow for two possibilities: the sound \softline
results from striking either the body of another or one's own.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 31.}{\plain \fs24   A much-debated verse.  Here our translation follows Petrocchi (}{\plain \fs24 \i La Commedia \softline
secondo l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 , Introduzione), pp. 168-69, who reads (}{\plain \fs24 \i error}{\plain \fs24  and not }{\plain \fs24 \i orror}{\plain \fs24 ), even \softline
though we agree with Giorgio Brugnoli ("}{\plain \fs24 \i Orror}{\plain \fs24 /}{\plain \fs24 \i Error}{\plain \fs24  [}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  III.31],"}{\plain \fs24 \i  Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24  54 \softline
[1982], pp. 15-30), that this is a likely echo of the }{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  (II.559): 'At me tum primum \softline
circumstetit horror.'  There are detailed discussions of the debate over the verse in Mazzoni \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: \softline
Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 352-55; in Petrocchi, (}{\plain \fs24 \i La Commedia secondo l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24 , pp. \softline
42-43); and in Maria Simonelli (}{\plain \fs24 \i Lectura Dantis Americana: "Inferno" III}{\plain \fs24  [Philadelphia: \softline
University of Pennsylvania Press, 1993], pp. 27-30.  As Petrocchi says, both readings are \softline
acceptable: there is not so much at stake here.  Nonetheless, the view of John Taaffe is worth \softline
noting (}{\plain \fs24 \i A Comment on the "Divine Comedy" of Dante Alighieri}{\plain \fs24  [London, John Murray, 1822]), \softline
p. 171: '...I tend to accept [}{\plain \fs24 \i orror}{\plain \fs24 ] without reserve, not because it is the most intelligible and \softline
poetical... on what I take to be the very best possible authority -- that of Boccaccio.'  (The \softline
recovery of Taaffe's all-but-forgotten English commentary to the first eight cantos is a bonus \softline
found in Simonelli's discussion.)\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 34-36.}{\plain \fs24   For the history of the interpretation of this tercet, now generally understood to \softline
indicate the presence in the 'ante-inferno,' or vestibule of hell, of the neutrals, those who never \softline
took a side, see Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 355-67.  And, for the existence of exactly such a \softline
