posthumous lot; but their foul condition is such that they are envious of every other class of \softline
sinners.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 50.}{\plain \fs24   }{\plain \fs24 \i Misericordia e giustizia}{\plain \fs24  ('Mercy and justice') are here to be understood as heaven \softline
and hell, neither of which will entertain any report of such vile creatures.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 52-57.}{\plain \fs24   Dante's essential technique for indicating the crucial moral failures of his various \softline
groups of sinners is here before us for the first time.  The neutrals, who never took a side, are \softline
portrayed as an organized crowd following a banner: exactly what they were not in life (e.g., the \softline
neutral angels who neither rebelled directly against God nor stood with Him, but who kept to one \softline
side).  And in this respect the neutrals are punished by being forced to assume a pose antithetic \softline
to that which they struck in life.  At the same time, the banner that they follow is the very \softline
essence of indeterminacy.  Not only is there no identifying sign on it, but is not held in the \softline
anchoring hand of any standard-bearer; it is a parody of the standard that is raised before a body \softline
of men who follow a leader.  Elsewhere we will encounter other such symbolic artifacts.  In \softline
Dante's hell the punishment of sin involves the application of opposites and similarities.  Here \softline
the sinners do the opposite of what they did (form into an organized group) and the same (follow \softline
no fixed purpose).  This form of just retribution is what Dante will later refer to as the 
}{\plain \fs24 \i contrapasso}{\plain \fs24  (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XXVIII.142).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 54.}{\plain \fs24   The word in rhyme position, }{\plain \fs24 \i indegna}{\plain \fs24 , has caused some anxiety.  In what way is the \softline
banner 'unworthy' of repose?  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": \softline
"Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), p. 388, proposes understanding the word as \softline
having the meaning 'insusceptible.'  This banner, by its very nature, seems incapable of ever \softline
coming to rest.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 58-60.}{\plain \fs24   The most-debated passage of this canto, at least in the modern era.  Many of the \softline
early commentators were convinced that this passage clearly intended a biting reference to Pope \softline
Celestine V (Pier da Morrone), who abdicated the papacy in 1294 after having held the office for \softline
less than four months.  He was followed into it by Dante's great ecclesiastical enemy, Pope \softline
Boniface VIII, and there are colorful contemporary accounts that would have it that Boniface \softline
mimicked the voice of the Holy Spirit in the air passages that led to Celestine's bed chamber, \softline
counseling his abdication.  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": \softline
"Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 390-415, offers a thorough history of the \softline
interpretation of the verse.  Two factors led to growing uneasiness with the identification of \softline
Celestine: (1) in 1313 he had been canonized, (2) ca. 1346 Francesco Petrarca, in his }{\plain \fs24 \i De vita \softline
solitaria}{\plain \fs24 , had defended the motives for his abdication.  Thus, beginning with the second \softline
redaction of the commentary of Pietro di Dante, certainty that the vile self-recuser was Celestine \softline
began to waiver.  The names of many others have been proposed, including those of Esau and \softline
Pontius Pilate.  It seems fair to say that there are fatal objections to all of these other candidacies.  \softline
For strong, even convincing, support for that of Celestine see Giorgio Padoan ("Colui che fece \softline
per vilt{\f2 \'42} il gran rifiuto," }{\plain \fs24 \i Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24  38 [1961], pp. 75-128) and Maria Simonelli (}{\plain \fs24 \i Lectura \softline
Dantis Americana: "Inferno" III}{\plain \fs24  [Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 1993]), pp. 41-58.  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  \softline
[Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 414-15, ends his lengthy study of the problem opting for (as had \softline
Sapegno [comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.59-60] before him), a generic sinner, unspecified, but standing for all \softline
who had made so vile a choice.  Yet Mazzoni's own evidence and arguments, as well as Dante's \softline
usual procedures, which tend to avoid such indeterminacy, help to convince this reader that it \softline
was indeed Celestine that Dante had in mind, as is underlined by his later scathing reference to \softline
the event of 'the great refusal' in}{\plain \fs24 \i  Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XXVII.104-105.  Further, Dante tells us that he 'saw and \softline
knew' (that is, recognized) this shade: there is nothing indeterminate in such a locution.  Nardi's \softline
telling objections to Petrocchi's denial that Dante would have put Celestine, canonized in 1313, \softline
in hell (}{\plain \fs24 \i Itinerari danteschi}{\plain \fs24  [Milan: Franco Angeli, 1994 (1969) pp. 41-59], first published in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Studi Romani}{\plain \fs24  in 1955) are today found in }{\plain \fs24 \i Dal "Convivio" alla "Commedia,"}{\plain \fs24  pp. 315-30.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 62.}{\plain \fs24   M. Barbi (}{\plain \fs24 \i Problemi di critica dantesca}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1934]), p. 203: here \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i cattivi}{\plain \fs24  means 'vile ones,' a stronger meaning than the word has sometimes in early (or in modern) \softline
Italian.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 64-69.}{\plain \fs24   The second descriptive passage that indicates the condition of these sinners \softline
continues the }{\plain \fs24 \i contrapasso}{\plain \fs24  (see }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XXVIII.142).  Now we see that these beings, who lacked all \softline
inner stimulation, are stung (}{\plain \fs24 \i stimolati}{\plain \fs24 ) by noxious insects.  Their tears mix with the blood drawn \softline
by these wounds only to serve as food for worms.  Dante's personal hatred for those who, unlike \softline
him, never made their true feelings or opinions known irradiates this canto.  There is not a single 
