in Revelation 3:1: 'Nomen habes quod vivas, et mortuus es' (you have the name of the living, and \softline
are dead), a fitting castigation for Dante to have had in mind for the neutrals.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 70-71.}{\plain \fs24   These verses mark a split between the second and third scenes of the canto, the \softline
neutrals and those other sinners, of all kinds, who are destined to begin their travel to their final \softline
destinations in Charon's bark.  From this point on the action of the canto moves to the near bank \softline
of Acheron.  The next canto will begin on the other side of the river. \par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 72-75.}{\plain \fs24   Dante asks two things of his guide, the identity of those gathered at the river's \softline
bank and the reason for their apparent eagerness to cross over.  His questions seem more or less \softline
similar to those he had asked at}{\plain \fs24 \i  Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.33, when he wanted to know the identity of the wailing \softline
souls who turn out to be the neutrals.  On that occasion, Virgil answers him immediately; on this, \softline
as we soon see, he is much less forthcoming.  See the note, below, to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.76-78).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
