III.72), followed by his student, Bernardino Daniello (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.70-81), cite apposite \softline
lines from Virgil (Aen. VI.318-319), Aeneas's inquiry of the Sibyl as to the motives leading the \softline
dead to desire to cross Acheron: 'dic,' ait, 'o virgo, quid volt concursus ad amnem? / quidve \softline
petunt animae?'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 73.}{\plain \fs24   The word }{\plain \fs24 \i costume}{\plain \fs24 , which we have translated as 'inner law,' is explained by Sapegno \softline
(comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.73) as 'istinto diventato norma e legge' (an instinct become a norm, even a \softline
