}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 75.}{\plain \fs24   The 'dim light': Dante's first experience of hell proper was one of utter darkness.  \softline
Indeed, his first sense impressions of the neutrals are entirely auditory (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.22-33).  Now the \softline
character himself assures us that he can see at least a little.  'In this third canto, Dante had to \softline
arrive at this solution: after beginning in an absolute darkness that forced him to perceive the \softline
external world only through sound, he begins to see once he passes the infernal gate and his eyes \softline
adapt to the darkness.  Now he speaks of 'dim light,' thus resolving the problem of vision in a \softline
world without light, in the world of eternal darkness' (Maria Simonelli [}{\plain \fs24 \i Lectura Dantis \softline
