}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 76-78.}{\plain \fs24   Virgil's rather clipped response, in marked contrast with his ready response to \softline
Dante's question about the identity of the neutrals (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.34-42), causes Dante to feel ashamed \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.79-81).  The exact reason for Virgil's reproof is a matter of some debate.  One might \softline
argue that his point is that Dante has gotten ahead of himself.  In the first instance, he asked \softline
about the nature of those he saw displayed just before him.  Now he is anticipating, literally \softline
looking ahead, and Virgil warns him against such behavior.  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo \softline
commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 419-22, surveys the dispute, which probably began with Benvenuto da Imola (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.76-78).  Perhaps the most interesting hypothesis was advanced by Mattalia (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.76-78), who argued that Virgil is upset that Dante, who had offered himself as a devoted reader of \softline
the }{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . I.82-86), does not recognize this place, so fully described by Virgil in his Sixth \softline
Book.  Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24  \softline
[Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp. 420-21, disagrees, finding this argument over-subtle.  We can \softline
say that once Virgil is ready to respond, he is courtesy itself (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.121-129).  The point seems \softline
to be that he now wants Dante first to observe Charon, whose words and actions will make many \softline
things clear, before getting into the details of this scene along the river's edge.  Nonetheless, \softline
Mattalia's point does seem to have some merit, particularly because Dante's guide mentions the \softline
name of the river (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.78), 'Acheronte.'  Had he not wanted to remind Dante of the Virgilian \softline
roots of this current experience of an underworld, would he not have merely said, 'the river,' \softline
leaving the identification for later?  This small moment of interpretive difficulty may stand as \softline
but one example of two things: the difficulty of this poem and the extraordinarily subtle \softline
exertions it calls forth from its commentators, whether its author always hoped for them or not.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 85.}{\plain \fs24   Charon's address to the wicked souls awaiting transport reinforces the hopelessness \softline
of this place, which was initially insisted on by the writing over the gate of hell (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.9), \softline
'lasciate ogne speranza, voi ch'entrate.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
