enunciates the principle {\u8219\'27}if Dante does not tell us, we are not meant to know{\u8219\'27} with specific \softline
reference to this crossing.  This reader does not find that an acceptable answer.  The moment is \softline
too important, surrounded by troubling and excited details, to be dealt with as anything less than \softline
a problematic mystery that the poet asks us to solve.  Mazzoni does his usual magisterial job in \softline
reporting the various theories to account for his transporter (Charon, an angel, Virgil, Beatrice, \softline
Lucia, some unnamed supernatural force).  But see the countering argument of Hollander,  \softline
"Dante on Horseback? (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  XII, 93-126)," }{\plain \fs24 \i Italica}{\plain \fs24  61 (1984), p. 292: 'We are in fact meant to \softline
understand that it is Charon who takes Dante across and that this }{\plain \fs24 \i crux}{\plain \fs24  is entirely the result of \softline
interpretive over-exertion that has made the self-evident confusing.  Charon indeed does wish to \softline
refuse Dante passage in his skiff (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.88-93); to his protestations Virgil responds as follows \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.94-96): 'Caron, non ti crucciare: / vuolsi cos{\f2 \'58} col{\f2 \'42} dove si puote / ci{\f2 \'62} che si vuole, e pi{\f2 \'6a} \softline
non dimandare.'  Daniello (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.95-96) has offered, in my opinion, a sufficient gloss \softline
to Virgil's words: 'E qui fanno le parole di Virgilio a Caronte quell'effetto che il mostrar \softline
dell'aureo ramo fa della Sibilla...' (Virgil's words have the same effect on Charon that the Sibyl's \softline
showing the golden bough had on him).  For Charon to be able to resist such a command would \softline
involve Dante in a theological or at least a poetic absurdity.  Cf. the similar moment at}{\plain \fs24 \i  Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.16-24, where Minos likewise would resist Dante's passage through his realm and where Virgil \softline
employs the same incantatory phrase that he had uttered in Canto III to achieve the same \softline
result....  Would Virgil have uttered the spell again had it not previously proved efficacious?  \softline
That seems a most doubtful proposition.  I believe that Dante's reason for not permitting us to \softline
witness the first scene being played out (we are given another version of the scene upon which it \softline
is modelled a bit later at}{\plain \fs24 \i  Inf}{\plain \fs24 . VIII.25-27) is that he found that poetic choice an excessive one, too \softline
self-consciously redolent of Aeneas's fanciful entrance into the underworld for him to make \softline
evident reference to it at this important moment, the threshold of his Christian afterworld.'  If this \softline
argument has merit, it accounts for the poet's reticence on poetic grounds.  Dante easily could \softline
have told us what he wants us to make ourselves responsible for; but that is not his way.  Rather, \softline
he makes us his partners in taking responsibility for such incredible details as these all through \softline
this incredible poem.  \par
